React native uses same codebase for both Android and IOS
1. Android App Development
Languages: Java, Kotlin
IDE (Development Tool): Android Studio
UI Frameworks: Jetpack Compose, XML-based layouts
Build System: Gradle
Testing Tools: Espresso, JUnit

2. iOS App Development
Languages: Swift, Objective-C
IDE (Development Tool): Xcode
UI Frameworks: SwiftUI, UIKit
Build System: Xcode Build System
Testing Tools: XCTest

npx @react-native-community/cli@latest init AwesomeProject  ( to create an app )

<View> replaces <div>  , <Text> replaces <p> or <span>.
No HTML, only JSX components.
Styling is done using StyleSheet API instead of CSS.

SCSS : Sassy CSS , It allows variables, nesting, and mixins, making styles more reusable and maintainable.
Example:
$primary-color: blue;
.container {
  background-color: $primary-color;
  color: white;
}

FOLDER STRUCTURE : 
1. android/ (Android-specific code)
AndroidManifest.xml → Contains Android app permissions & settings.
MainActivity.java → Entry point for the Android app.
build.gradle → Configuration file for dependencies & SDK version.

2. ios/ (iOS-specific code)
Info.plist → Contains iOS app metadata (permissions, display name, etc.).
AppDelegate.m → Entry point for the iOS app.
Podfile → Manages iOS dependencies using CocoaPods.

3. index.js (Entry Point)
4. App.js (Main App Component)
5. package.json (Project Config & Dependencies)
6. babel.config.js (Babel Configuration) - Babel helps transform modern JavaScript to be compatible with older environments.
7. metro.config.js (Metro Bundler Config)
